        "creation_date": 1407473475,
        "body": "<p>You can sort them by using the <code>Collections.sort<\/code> with some logic for sorting it by checking it first its length if it is equal to each other and parsing it to int. But you need to store the List of number first to a string so you can check the length and precision of the integer.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>sample:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Collections.sort(powerSet, new Comparator&lt;List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt;() {\n\n        @Override\n        public int compare(List&lt;Integer&gt; o1, List&lt;Integer&gt; o2) {\n            StringBuilder temp = new StringBuilder();\n            StringBuilder temp2 = new StringBuilder();\n            for (Integer i2 : o1) {\n                temp.append( i2 );\n            }\n            for (Integer i2 : o2) {\n                temp2.append( i2 );\n            }\n\n            if(temp.length() == temp2.length())\n                return Integer.parseInt(temp.toString()) - Integer.parseInt(temp2.toString());\n            else\n                return temp.length() - temp2.length();\n        }\n    });\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><strong>result:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>1 \n2 \n3 \n1 2 \n1 3 \n2 3 \n1 2 3 \n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
